## Remember to remove the reads identified as rRNA in the quant file.

3. Data Interpretation: Decoys vs. rRNA Targets
This pipeline handles "non-target" reads in two distinct ways:
A. Decoys (The Whole Genome)
The whole genome is marked as a decoy.
Behavior: If a read maps better to a non-coding intergenic region than to a gene, Salmon ignores it.
Result: These reads are not present in your quant.sf file. They are filtered out automatically to reduce noise.
B. rRNA Targets (The rrna.fa file)
The rRNA sequences are included as targets.
Behavior: Because rRNA is a major biological signal, we count it to "account" for the library composition.
Result: These reads ARE present in your quant.sf file with very high counts.
Downstream Action: You must filter out these rRNA rows in R before running DESeq2. If left in, the massive ribosomal counts will dominate the statistical normalization and lead to incorrect results.
